Cirbumbinary Planet: Kepler-16b
2020 June 21
Kepler-16b (formally Kepler-16 (AB)-b) is an extrasolar planet. It is a Saturn-mass planet consisting of half gas and half rock and ice, and it orbits a binary star, Kepler-16, with a period of 229 days. "It is the first confirmed, unambiguous example of a circumbinary planet – a planet orbiting not one, but two stars," said Josh Carter of the Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics, one of the discovery team.

Eclpising Binary: KOI-2570
2020 June 21
KOI-3570 (aliases: 2MASS J19405783+4009273, KIC 5023948, and WISE J194057.82+400927.3) is an eclipsing binary star system. The term KOI means exactly what the name implies – Kepler has declared these to be "objects of interest," not planetary candidates. KOI-3570 is a member of the old open cluster NGC 6819. NGC 6819 is an open cluster (commonly known as an "open star cluster") located 7,200 light years away in the Cygnus constellation. It was discovered by Caroline Herschel on 12 May 1784.
